# Probing Visual Language Priors in VLMs
Tiange Luo1,∗Ang Cao1,∗Gunhee Lee2Justin Johnson1,†Honglak Lee1,2,†
1University of Michigan2LG AI Research∗joint first authorship†equal advising
###### Abstract
Despite recent advances in Vision-Language Models (VLMs), many still over-rely on visual language priors existed in their training data rather than true visual reasoning. To examine the situation, we introduce ViLP, a visual question answering (VQA) benchmark that pairs each question with three potential answers and three corresponding images: one image whose answer can be inferred from text alone, and two images that demand visual reasoning. By leveraging image generative models, we ensure significant variation in*texture*,*shape*,*conceptual combinations*,*hallucinated elements*, and*proverb*-based contexts, making our benchmark images distinctly out-of-distribution. While humans achieve near-perfect accuracy, modern VLMs falter; for instance, GPT-4 achieves only 66.17% on ViLP. To alleviate this, we propose a self-improving framework in which models generate new VQA pairs and images, then apply pixel-level and semantic corruptions to form “good-bad” image pairs for self-training. Our training objectives compel VLMs to focus more on actual visual inputs and have demonstrated the effectiveness in enhancing the performance of open-source VLMs, including LLaVA-v1.5 and Cambrian.
### 1Introduction
Vision-Language Models (VLMs) have advanced text-image interaction, serving as a cornerstone in bridging the gap between visual and textual data> (Achiam et al., [> 2023
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib1)> ; Team et al., [> 2023
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib78)> )
. However, a persistent challenge for learning-based models, such as ResNets and CLIPs, is their reliance on strong priors overly learned in the training data, sometimes overlooking visual cues for answering questions> (Agrawal et al., [> 2016
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib3)> ; Prabhu et al., [> 2023
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib62)> )
. For example, when shown an image of a hexagonal moon (Figure[1](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#S1.F1)), a model might incorrectly assert that “the moon is round" due to strong language priors. Similarly, these models may adhere to learned visual priors> (Thrush et al., [> 2022
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib79)> ; Sterz et al., [> 2024
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib75)> )
, making it difficult for them to comprehend out-of-distribution visual cues, such as a zebra with atypical spot patterns (Figure[1](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#S1.F1)), where humans would easily discern the difference. This raises an important question: do today’s VLMs still over-rely on learned visual language priors?
To investigate this, we probe the visual language priors of VLMs by constructing Question-Image-Answer (QIA) triplets that deliberately deviate from the training data distribution. Unlike existing benchmarks that typically rely on internet-sourced images, which inadvertently favor the visual language priors embedded in training data, we utilize modern image generation models such as DALL·E-3> (Ramesh et al., [> 2021
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib66)> )
and[Flux](https://github.com/black-forest-labs/flux)to synthesize out-of-distribution images, supporting uncommon answers. To further challenge the priors of VLMs, we amplify the language priors in questions by introducing distractor facts, making the questions more suggestive.
Our benchmark, ViLP, contains 300 carefully designed questions, each paired with three distinct answers: a*Prior Answer*and two*Test Answers*, resulting in a total of 900 QIA triplets. Each question is structured to present adistractor factfollowed by aquestion. The distractor fact directly leads to the Prior Answer. In contrast, the two Test Answers are crafted to challenge the priors by requiring both textual and visual cues for accurate reasoning. While human participants can differentiate between all three answers, current VLMs face considerable difficulty, as evidenced by a significant performance drop in our benchmarks, with GPT-4o> (OpenAI, [> 2024
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib58)> )
scoring only 66.17%.
Inspired by ViLP  results, we propose a self-improving approach to encourage VLM reasoning more relying on visual inputs. Our method involves self-generating VQAs using image generation and editing models> (Podell et al., [> 2023
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib61)> ; Ren et al., [> 2024
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib67)> ; Brooks et al., [> 2023a
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib8)> )
and introducing controlled corruptions to create “good" and “bad" image pairs for DPO-like training> (Rafailov et al., [> 2024
](https://arxiv.org/html/2501.00569v1#bib.bib64)> )
